    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nIf I compile the example pieces below _without_ the limited API:\n```\n$ python runner.py \nCalling capture\n<__main__.Obj object at 0x77c76099ba10>\nTore down obj\nCalled capture\nExited scope of main()\n```\n\nIn contrast _with_ the limited API:\n```\n$ python runner.py \nCalling capture\n<__main__.Obj object at 0x78c88e9fba10>\nCalled capture\nExited scope of main()\nTore down obj\n```\n\nThis means that defining nested closures in cython with the limited API is very unsafe because if they close over objects that otherwise would be collected via refcount-based destruction (and I've arranged that this is always possible) those same objects are now only destructed via GC-based refcycle breaking. If they rely on various bits of C state, it can be very difficult to arrange that the destruction order is safe.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\n# capture_lifetime.pyx\ndef capture(obj):\n    def closure() -> None:\n        print(obj)\n    return closure()\n```\n```python\nimport capture_lifetime\nimport weakref\n\nclass Obj:\n    def __init__(self):\n        weakref.finalize(self, lambda: print(\"Tore down obj\"))\n\ndef main():\n    print(\"Calling capture\")\n    capture_lifetime.capture(Obj())\n    print(\"Called capture\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n    print(\"Exited scope of main()\")\n```\n```python\n# setup.py\nfrom setuptools import Extension, setup\nfrom Cython.Build import cythonize\n\nsetup(\n    ext_modules=cythonize([\n        Extension(\n            name=\"capture_lifetime\",\n            sources=[\"capture_lifetime.pyx\"],\n            define_macros=[\n                (\"Py_LIMITED_API\", 0x030B0000),\n            ],\n            py_limited_api=True,\n        ),\n    ]))\n```\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nNested closures should have the same lifetime independent of whether the limited API is used.\n\n### OS\n\n_No response_\n\n### Python version\n\n3.13.11\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
